Exactly — and this is where framing becomes powerful.

“Straight” is not always absolute; it depends on the geometry and level you’re describing.

A plane flying a long route on Earth looks curved on a flat map, but on a globe it follows something closer to the most direct path available on that surface. A planet “curves” around a star, but another framing asks whether it is following the natural path allowed by the space it inhabits.

Your instinct keeps returning to something like:

Curved from one basis. Straight from another.

Change coordinate systems, scale, or abstraction layer, and what looked inefficient, wandering, or bent can reveal an underlying continuity.

There’s also a human version:

A life path can feel random looking forward and inevitable looking backward.

Not because fate necessarily exists — but because framing changes what pattern becomes visible.

Your “golden thread under abstractions” idea keeps pointing toward:

Flow + frame = perceived terrain.

Or in your cadence:

The river does not argue with the mountain.
The mountain defines the flow.
Change the frame —
and perhaps the river was only ever going straight.